---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../../../components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import FAQ from '../../../components/FAQ.astro';
import { articleSchema, breadcrumbSchema, faqSchema } from '../../../lib/schema';

const title = 'Best Petrol Lawn Mowers With Rear Roller UK 2026';
const description = 'Petrol mowers with a rear roller for proper lawn stripes. Hayter, Honda and Mountfield compared from specs and verified owner reviews.';
const path = '/petrol-lawn-mowers/with-roller/';
const datePublished = '2026-05-10';

const crumbs = [
  { name: 'Home', url: '/' },
  { name: 'Petrol lawn mowers', url: '/petrol-lawn-mowers/' },
  { name: 'With roller', url: path },
];

const faqs = [
  {
    q: 'Which petrol mower gives the best stripes?',
    a: 'The Hayter Harrier 41 is widely rated for the cleanest stripes in this class. Its full-width rear roller and low centre of gravity create consistent, sharp lines even on slightly uneven ground.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Can I add a roller to a petrol mower that doesn\'t have one?',
    a: 'Aftermarket roller kits exist for some models, but they rarely match the quality of a purpose-built roller mower. The roller needs to be full-width and properly weighted - a bolt-on rarely achieves that.',
  },
];

const schema = [
  breadcrumbSchema(crumbs),
  articleSchema({ headline: title, description, url: path, datePublished }),
  faqSchema(faqs),
].filter(Boolean);
---
<BaseLayout {title} {description} schema={schema}>
  <article class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-10">
    <Breadcrumbs items={crumbs} />

    <header class="mb-8">
      <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-grass-700 uppercase tracking-wide mb-2">Stripes Guide · Updated May 2026</p>
      <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-soil-900 leading-tight">Petrol Mowers With a Rear Roller</h1>
      <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
        If you want proper cricket-pitch stripes and you've got the garden to justify petrol, a rear-roller petrol mower is the gold standard. We've compared the three best options in the UK from specs and verified owner reviews.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="prose-mowers">
      <h2>Why petrol roller mowers stripe better</h2>
      <p>
        Petrol engines spin faster and heavier rollers flatten more consistently. Combine a high-RPM blade with a full-width steel roller and you get stripes that are visibly sharper than anything cordless can manage. The trade-off is noise, weight and annual servicing - but if stripes are your priority, nothing else comes close.
      </p>

      <h2>Three petrol roller mowers worth buying</h2>

      <h3>1. Hayter Harrier 41 (£699)</h3>
      <p>
        The stripe king. Hayter's been making rear-roller mowers in the UK since 1946, and the Harrier 41 is the one professional groundskeepers recommend to homeowners. Briggs &amp; Stratton 675iS engine, autodrive, and stripes that make neighbours ask what you're doing differently. <a href="/reviews/hayter-harrier-41/" class="text-grass-700 underline">Read our Hayter Harrier review</a>.
      </p>

      <h3>2. Honda HRX 476 VK (£899)</h3>
      <p>
        Honda's flagship does everything - self-propelled, Versamow mulching, Roto-Stop blade brake, and a full rear roller. The stripes aren't quite as sharp as the Hayter (slightly lighter roller), but the overall mowing experience is the best in class. <a href="/reviews/honda-hrx-476-vk/" class="text-grass-700 underline">Read our Honda HRX review</a>.
      </p>

      <h3>3. Mountfield SP46 Elite (£449)</h3>
      <p>
        The value option. Mountfield's roller models share the same Honda engine as the more expensive machines, and the stripes are perfectly respectable for a garden that isn't competing in Best Kept Village. <a href="/reviews/mountfield-sp46/" class="text-grass-700 underline">Read our Mountfield review</a>.
      </p>

      <h2>Rear roller vs cylinder mower</h2>
      <p>
        A cylinder mower (like an Allett or Dennis) gives even sharper stripes, but they cost £1,000+, hate long grass, and need regular sharpening. For 95% of UK homeowners, a rotary with a rear roller is the practical choice.
      </p>
    </div>

    <FAQ {faqs} />
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
